This topic describes the process of creating a UAA client for the BOSH Director. Creating an automation client is necessary if you are running BOSH from a script or continuous integration pipeline.

## <a id="opsman-login"></a> UAAC installed on Ops Manager

The UAAC client is installed on the Ops Manager virtual machine. Log in to the Ops Manager VM and target the Director.

### <a id="operator-tools-tasks"></a> Log in to the Ops Manager VM

1. Open a terminal and ssh into the Ops Manager VM. When prompted, enter your password.
	<pre class='terminal'>
    $ ssh ubuntu@OPS-MANAGER-FQDN
    Password: ***********
  </pre>

1. Navigate to the Ops Manager **Installation Dashboard** >> **Status** and copy the **Ops Manager Director** IP address. Target the UAA on the Director VM using the IP address. The root certificate is also available at the following endpoint:

    `https://ops-manager/api/v0/security/root_ca_certificate</api/v0/security/root_ca_certificate.`

    <pre class='terminal'>
    $ uaac target http<span>s</span>://director-ip:8443 --ca-cert \
    /var/tempest/workspaces/default/root_ca_certificate

    Target: http<span>s</span>://10.85.16.4:8443
    </pre>

1. Log in to the UAA and get the owner token. Find the UAA password for the login user at `https://<FQDN>/api/v0/deployed/director/credentials/uaa_login_client_credentials
    `

	 <pre class='terminal'>
    $ uaac token owner get login -s <PasswordForUAALoginUser>
    User name:  admin
  	Password:  ********************

  	Successfully fetched token via owner password grant.
  	Target: http<span>s</span>://10.85.16.4:8443
  	Context: admin, from client login
    </pre>

1. Create a new UAA Client with `bosh admin` privileges.

    <pre class='terminal'>
    $ uaac client add ci --authorized_grant_types client_credentials \
    --authorities bosh.admin --secret CREATE-A-SECRET

    scope: uaa.none
    client_id: ci
    resource_ids: none
    authorized_grant_types: client_credentials
    autoapprove:
    action: none
    authorities: bosh.admin
    name: ci
    lastmodified: 1469727130702
    id: ci
    </pre>

1. Set the client and secret as environment variables on the VM.

	<pre class='terminal'>
   	$ ubuntu@ip-10-0-0-12:~$ export BOSH_CLIENT=ci
  	$ ubuntu@ip-10-0-0-12:~$ export BOSH_CLIENT_SECRET=cipassword
	</pre>

1. Target BOSH using the client, using the **Ops Manager Director** IP address you obtained above.
	
	<pre class='terminal'>
  	$ bosh --ca-cert /var/tempest/workspaces/default/root_ca_certificate \
  	target "${OPS_MANAGER_DIRECTOR_IP}"
	</pre>


